courses.learning_outcomes:
At the end of this course, students are expected to:

1. Grasp the distinctive features of different curriculum development models;
2. Understand the principles that underpin the ECE curriculum and assessment designs;
3. Offer analysis and personal opinions on selected curriculum issues in ECE; and

4. Reflect on their own practices related to curriculum development in ECE.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

• Appreciate the complexity of real life in school;
• Develop an integrative perspective about organizational life in school;
• Become an independent and critical thinker;
• Employ organizational theory as a lens to interpret everyday organizational life;
• Apply theories to improve organizational practice;
• Explore management practices across cultural boundaries;
• Understand the new roles emerging in organizations as a result of innovations in technology.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of this course, students are expected:
1. to have a basic understanding of general perspectives on education;
2. to be able to reflect on the meaning and significance of the key issues in early childhood education;
3. to relate their own experience to the concepts and theories learnt in the course.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to:
1) identify different forms of signs and their richness;
2) recognize multi-modal meaning making in children's experience with signs and the role of the signs mediation in the development of children's higher psychological processes;
3) design and/or evaluate the effectiveness of early childhood educational activities applying the rationales behind the perspectives of semiotics and cognitive theories.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)
